    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1875-04-07T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1875-04-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="59"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d59">
                <head>No. 55.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Reynolds</persName> to Mr. <persName
                            type="to">Fish</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of the United States</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">La Paz, Bolivia</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1875-04-07">
                            <hi rend="italic">April</hi> 7, 1875</date>. (Received May
                        13.)</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 62.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Referring to my dispatches Nos. 58 and 59, in
                    relation to the attempted revolution of the 20th ultimo, in La Paz, I have the
                    honor to inform the Department that I have refused asylum in this legation to
                    all persons engaged in the burning, of the palace building, as described in my
                    dispatches referred to.<note n="*" xml:id="d59fn1">See dispatches 56 and
                        57.</note> I was impelled to make this decision from the fact that, had they
                    succeeded in their attempt to completely destroy the building by fire and set
                    match to the magazine of powder, the United States would have had no
                    legation-room in La Paz, if indeed any “minister-resident” living.</p>
                <p>The further fact that the government of Bolivia could rightfully demand them as
                    criminals, to be tried by the courts of the country for incendiarism and murder,
                    was a serious obstacle to my receiving them in asylum.</p>
                <p>Asking the approval of the Department for my official action in the premises,</p>
                <p>I am, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>R. M. REYNOLDS.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
